{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656583"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18751"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18751"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11483"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62835"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10444"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26583"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESound waves travel through the external auditory canal and cause the tympanic membrane to vibrate. These vibrations are essential for normal hearing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the movement pattern of the tympanic membrane in response to sound waves?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rotational movement around a central axis","Maximum vibration at the peripheral edges","Static centre with peripheral movement only","Equal vibration across the entire membrane","Maximum vibration at the centre with rigid peripheral attachment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaximum vibration at the centre with rigid peripheral attachment\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes how the tympanic membrane moves in response to sound waves. The membrane is firmly attached at its periphery by the fibrocartilaginous ring (annulus tympanicus), while the central portion containing the umbo moves with the greatest amplitude in a piston-like motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual vibration across the entire membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - The membrane\u0027s movement varies across its surface due to its anatomical attachments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximum vibration at the peripheral edges\u003C/strong\u003E - The edges are actually the most firmly anchored part with minimal movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotational movement around a central axis\u003C/strong\u003E - The membrane moves in and out rather than rotating\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStatic centre with peripheral movement only\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the actual movement pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern of movement allows for efficient transfer of sound energy from the air to the ossicular chain, with the central displacement being approximately twice that of the average displacement across the entire membrane.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The tympanic membrane vibrates maximally at its centre due to the rigid attachment at its periphery.","Sound waves cause the tympanic membrane to move inward and outward in a piston-like motion.","The umbo region of the tympanic membrane has the greatest amplitude of movement in response to sound."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62835"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18751"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62835"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T16:19:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T16:20:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11483"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","s